INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'e4294122-abe7-489e-beac-f92c21ab96f0',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$the_graph Web3 Essentials: Ethers.js with Providers, Signers, and Contract Interaction$escape$,
  $escape$When working with the_graph, you often need to interact with Ethereum contracts. Ethers.js is a popular library for this purpose. To use it with the_graph, you'll need to create a provider instance, passing the GraphQL endpoint and a signatory. A provider is responsible for fetching data from the blockchain. You can create a provider with ` ethers.getDefaultProvider() ` or ` ethers.providers.JsonRpcProvider() `. For example, to use the Infura provider with the_graph's default endpoint, you'd do: `const provider = new ethers.providers.JsonRpcProvider('https://api.thegraph.com/subgraphs/name/your-subgraph-name');`. A signer is required to send transactions. You can create a signer with a private key or a hardware wallet. Once you have a provider and signer, you can interact with contracts using ` ethers.Contract() `. You can also listen to events emitted by contracts using ` ethers.Contract.getEvent().getFilter() `. The event listener will notify you when an event is emitted.$escape$,
  $escape$import { ethers } from 'ethers';
const provider = new ethers.providers.JsonRpcProvider('https://api.thegraph.com/subgraphs/name/your-subgraph-name');
const contract = new ethers.Contract('0xYourContractAddress', ['YourContractABI'], provider);
contract.on('YourEvent', (event) => {
  console.log(event);
});$escape$,
  $escape$typescript$escape$,
